<subSubSection id="F187F25A07D7BC8DAD9037235803EF21" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="EEF4EC54000F4F2B7316B9801861D9FC" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="75857D50D441F6F41F212D886CF2EA17" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">
<bibRefCitation id="F23B155AD3260C3F7FE3042B2B0EB7AC" author="Verity, R" journalOrPublisher="Entomologist's Record" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" pagination="193 - 201" refId="B97" refString="Verity, R, 1919. Seasonal Polymorphism and Races of Some European Grypocera and Rhopalocera. Entomologist's Record 31: 193 - 201" title="Seasonal Polymorphism and Races of Some European Grypocera and Rhopalocera." volume="31" year="1919">Verity (1919)</bibRefCitation>
proposed this name as a 
<normalizedToken id="B27E6F0E3D7E05E91CA4EFA69452C97A" originalValue="“race”">&quot;race&quot;</normalizedToken>
of 
<taxonomicName id="00221DFCE5A3EAAFE3A03D5BB9B01001" baseAuthorityName="Rottemburg" baseAuthorityYear="1775" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Melitaea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Melitaea athalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="athalia">
<emphasis id="2AEFD39A67606D32386C91877DFD6E72" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="193">Melitaea athalia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Rottemburg, 1775). According to 
<bibRefCitation id="BAD4BA4CD2DC39D838C7E66FFA39F098" author="Kudrna, O" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Research on the Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="193" pagination="1 - 105" refId="B56" refString="Kudrna, O, 1983. An annotated catalogue of the butterflies named by Roger Verity. Journal of Research on the Lepidoptera 21 (1): 1 - 105" title="An annotated catalogue of the butterflies named by Roger Verity." volume="21" year="1983">Kudrna (1983</bibRefCitation>
: 83-84), this name is available as subspecific. The year on the specimen labels (1937) indicate specimens were collected 18 years after description (1919) from the same location the original holotype material was collected. As a result, the black label of the specimens treated as 
<normalizedToken id="74C75A05B50E844EC74FF1EC12966AF2" originalValue="“types”">&quot;types&quot;</normalizedToken>
is erroneous. The specimen collected from the same geographical location from which the type specimen was collected is called topotype. According to ICZN (1999), a topotype has no formal standing and is not regulated by the Code. Therefore, these six specimens are erroneously labelled as types, should be annotated as &quot;Not a Type&quot; and are treated here as 
<normalizedToken id="1956D1318F42486470A99AAFAE8AB5AE" originalValue="“Non-type”">&quot;Non-type&quot;</normalizedToken>
specimens
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
